            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/assets"]""",
            Tags = """["assets","equipment","tooling"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Assets Overview\n\nThe Assets module is your equipment and tooling register. It tracks every physical asset your shop owns or manages — machines, tooling, vehicles, and facilities — along with their maintenance history, current status, operating hours, and acquisition/accounting details.\n\n### What Counts as an Asset?\n\nAssets are categorized by type:\n- **Machine** — CNC mills, lathes, saws, presses, and other production equipment\n- **Tooling** — molds, dies, jigs, fixtures, and cutting tools (includes customer-owned tooling)\n- **Facility** — buildings, HVAC systems, electrical panels, and infrastructure\n- **Vehicle** — delivery trucks, forklifts, company vehicles\n- **Other** — anything that doesn't fit the above categories\n\n### Two Kinds of Extra Fields\n\nEvery asset shares the core identity fields (name, type, location, manufacturer, model, serial). Beyond those, two distinct field groups appear:\n\n1. **Acquisition & Accounting** — shown for **every** asset type. Capture what it cost, how it depreciates, the work center it's stationed at, and its accounting code. These describe what the asset cost and how its value drops over time.\n2. **Tooling-only fields** — shown **only** when the type is Tooling. Capture whether a customer owns it, the cavity count, and the tool life. These describe how a mold or die runs in production.\n\nSo tooling fields are *not* the only extras — the Acquisition & Accounting section applies to a CNC mill or a forklift just as much as to a mold.\n\n### How Assets Connect to Other Features\n\n**Tooling and Parts:** A tooling asset can be linked to a specific part (the part it produces) and to the job that created it. This gives you full traceability: which mold makes which part, and which job built the mold.\n\n**Maintenance:** Each asset tracks its maintenance history — scheduled maintenance, repairs, and inspections. When an asset is set to Maintenance status, it signals to the team that the machine is down. Downtime events (unplanned breakdowns) and recurring maintenance schedules are tracked separately — see the dedicated downtime and maintenance-schedule modules.\n\n**Accounting:** When your accounting system is connected, the asset's accounting code fills in automatically. When nothing is connected, you enter it yourself.\n\n**Barcode/QR Labels:** Every asset gets a barcode/QR label you can print for quick identification on the shop floor. Scan the label to pull up the asset record instantly.\n\n### When to Use Assets\n\n- When onboarding a new piece of equipment (and recording what it cost)\n- When tracking customer-owned tooling (molds they send you)\n- When scheduling or recording maintenance, or logging a breakdown\n- When an asset goes out of service and you need to track why\n- When you need to know the shot count or tool life remaining on a mold","sections":[]}"""
