            ContentJson = """{"title":"Asset Acquisition & Accounting","groups":[{"heading":"Where to Find It","items":[{"label":"Location","value":"The Acquisition section sits below the main fields (name, type, location, manufacturer, model, serial, notes) when you add an asset."},{"label":"Applies to","value":"EVERY asset type — Machine, Tooling, Facility, Vehicle, Other. It's separate from the Tooling-only fields, which show only when the type is Tooling."},{"label":"When to fill it","value":"When you first add the asset. All four fields are optional, so you can leave them blank and add them later with Edit."}]},{"heading":"The Four Fields","items":[{"label":"Acquisition Cost","value":"What the asset cost to buy. Must be zero or more and no higher than one billion — anything outside that blocks Save."},{"label":"Depreciation Method","value":"How the asset's value drops over time. Choose Straight Line, Declining Balance, Units of Production, or leave it blank."},{"label":"Work Center","value":"The work center where the asset runs, entered by its work-center number. Ties the asset to where it physically sits."},{"label":"GL Account","value":"The accounting code the asset maps to."}]},{"heading":"GL Account & Your Accounting System","items":[{"label":"Accounting system connected","value":"When your accounting system (such as QuickBooks) is connected, the GL account fills in automatically — you don't type it."},{"label":"Nothing connected","value":"With no accounting system connected, you enter the GL account yourself."},{"label":"Depreciation schedules","value":"Forge stores the depreciation method on the asset but doesn't work out the full schedule — that stays in your accounting system. The method here is just for reference and export."}]},{"heading":"Editing Later","items":[{"label":"How to change them","value":"Open the asset (click its row), click the pencil (Edit), change the values, and Save. It's the same form used to add an asset."},{"label":"Common mistake","value":"Thinking cost and depreciation are tooling-only. They aren't — a forklift or a CNC mill records its purchase details in the very same section."}]}]}"""
