        {
            Title = "Tracking Asset Downtime",
            Slug = "assets-downtime",
            Summary = "What asset downtime is, how breakdown logging works, and how starting and ending a downtime event differs from the Maintenance status.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/assets"]""",
            Tags = """["assets","downtime","breakdown","maintenance"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Tracking Asset Downtime\n\nWhen a machine breaks down mid-shift, you lose production time you usually want to measure. **Downtime tracking** records each unplanned outage as its own event with a start, an end, and a reason — so you can total downtime hours per asset and spot the machines that keep failing.\n\nDowntime tracking is a feature your install can turn on or off. If it's turned off, you won't see downtime data at all.\n\n### Downtime vs. the Maintenance Status\n\nThese two are easy to confuse:\n\n- **Maintenance status** (the yellow label you set on the detail panel) is a *right-now flag*. It tells the team \"this machine is unavailable right now.\" It doesn't track how long.\n- **A downtime event** is a *time record*. It has a start time, an end time, and a reason. While a downtime event is open, the asset is treated as down; when you end it, the clock stops and the elapsed time is saved.\n\nUse the status to signal availability on the floor; use a downtime event when you need the *hours* for reliability or cost reporting.\n\n### The Life of a Downtime Event\n\n1. **A machine goes down.** Something fails — a spindle alarm, a hydraulic leak, a power fault.\n2. **Start a downtime log** for that asset and record the reason. The event is now open (no end time yet).\n3. **Optionally set the asset's status** to Maintenance or Out of Service so the floor sees it's unavailable.\n4. **The machine comes back up.** End the downtime event — the end time is stamped and the elapsed hours join the asset's downtime total.\n5. **Set the status back to Active** so the asset is available again.\n\nAn asset can rack up many downtime events over its life; each is its own record tied to that asset.\n\n### Who Records Downtime\n\nDowntime is tracked per asset and can be listed for one asset or across the whole shop. Those totals are what drive your reliability numbers and feed the maintenance forecasts, so a machine's failure history is worth getting right. In practice a supervisor or maintenance tech records it, not every operator.\n\n### Good Habits\n\n- **Start the event when the machine actually stops, not when you get around to it** — the times are what make the hours meaningful.\n- **Always end the event when the machine is back** — an event left open looks like the machine is still down and inflates your totals.\n- **Write a real reason** — \"spindle bearing\" is far more useful three months later than \"broke.\"\n- **Pair it with the status** — a downtime event for the hours, a Maintenance or Out-of-Service status for the at-a-glance signal.\n\n### Related\n\n- *Asset Maintenance Schedules* — for planned, recurring maintenance (versus the unplanned breakdowns here).\n- *Assets Overview* — for the status labels and the difference between Maintenance, Retired, and Out of Service.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Asset Maintenance Schedules (Article) ────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Asset Maintenance Schedules",
            Slug = "assets-maintenance-schedules",
            Summary = "How recurring maintenance schedules, maintenance logs, and maintenance jobs fit together — plus how to read an asset's maintenance history.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/assets"]""",
            Tags = """["assets","maintenance","schedule","pm"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Asset Maintenance Schedules\n\nPlanned maintenance is the opposite of a breakdown: instead of reacting to a failure, you service the asset on a regular interval to *prevent* one. Forge does this with three connected pieces — **schedules**, **logs**, and **maintenance jobs**. These require the preventive-maintenance feature to be turned on for your install.\n\n### The Three Pieces\n\n1. **Maintenance Schedule** — a repeating plan attached to an asset (\"grease the ways every 250 hours,\" \"replace the filter every 90 days\"). It sets *what* should happen and *how often*. An asset can have several.\n2. **Maintenance Log** — a record that a maintenance task was actually done. Each log captures the schedule it covered, when it was done, who did it, hours spent, cost, and notes. Logging maintenance closes the loop on a schedule and builds history.\n3. **Maintenance Job** — when a due task needs real shop work (a technician, parts, time tracking), you can start a Job from the schedule. That Job moves across the board like any other work and ties the maintenance back to your normal job tracking.\n\n### Who Can Do What\n\nCreating and managing schedules, logging maintenance, and starting maintenance jobs are **Admin and Manager actions**. A regular operator can *see* an asset's maintenance history but usually won't be the one creating schedules. If you don't have the right access, those management actions won't show up for you.\n\n### Reading an Asset's Maintenance History\n\nAnyone with asset access can view this. Open an asset (click its row) and scroll to the **Maintenance History** section. For each past service you'll see:\n\n- **Schedule name** — which plan it covered\n- **Performed date** — when it was done\n- **Performed by** — the technician's name\n- **Hours spent** — the labor hours\n- **Cost** — the parts and labor cost\n- **Notes** — anything the tech wrote down\n\nIf the asset has never been serviced, you'll see a \"No maintenance logs\" message with a wrench icon. This section is read-only — it shows the services that have been logged; it isn't where you create them.\n\n### How It All Connects\n\n- A **schedule** says a task is due.\n- Doing the task creates a **log** (which then shows in Maintenance History).\n- If the task needs tracked shop work, it becomes a **maintenance Job**.\n- Operating **hours** (see the Field Reference) are how usage-based schedules know when they're due — keep hours current so they come due on time.\n\n### Schedules vs. Downtime vs. Predictive\n\n- **Maintenance schedules** = *planned*, repeating, by calendar or by hours.\n- **Downtime events** = *unplanned* breakdowns you log after the fact (see *Tracking Asset Downtime*).\n- **Predictive maintenance** = the separate Maintenance area, where the system forecasts likely failures so you can schedule against a prediction. The schedules here are the manual, rule-based version.","sections":[]}"""
        });

