            Tags = """["assets","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Depreciation & Cost — What to Enter, and Why\n\nThe Acquisition section holds two purchase details on every asset. You're recording them for reference and reporting, not doing the bookkeeping here.\n\n- **Depreciation Method** — pick Straight Line, Declining Balance, or Units of Production, or leave it blank. Straight Line spreads the cost evenly over the asset's life; Declining Balance writes off more in the early years; Units of Production ties the write-off to how hard the asset runs (a good fit for a machine or mold that ages by cycles, not calendar). Forge just records which method you chose — it doesn't work out the year-by-year schedule. That stays in your accounting system.\n- **Acquisition Cost** — what you paid, and it's optional. Enter a real purchase price; a wildly high number (into the billions) is treated as a typo and won't save. Leave it blank on assets where cost isn't tracked and it simply stays empty.\n\nTip: fill these in when the equipment first arrives, while the invoice is still in front of you. Chasing a purchase price two years later is a lot harder.\n\n## How the GL Account Hands Off to Accounting\n\nThe GL account is the hand-off point between the asset register and your books.\n\n- **Accounting system connected** — when your accounting system (such as QuickBooks) is connected, the GL account comes from it automatically, so you don't type it.\n- **Nothing connected** — with no accounting system, you enter the GL account by hand.\n\nEither way, the heavy accounting — depreciation schedules, the general ledger, bank reconciliation — is never done here. The asset register keeps the reference (which account, which method) so a machine, mold, or forklift can be tied back to the books; the actual entries live in accounting. If you're a maintenance or plant user, treat these fields as \"note what it cost and which bucket it belongs to\" and let the office handle the rest.\n\n## Predictive Maintenance\n\nCondition monitoring and failure forecasting live in the separate **Maintenance** area, not on the Assets page. Assets is your equipment register — identity, status, hours, tooling, and purchase details. The Maintenance feature reads those same assets and layers analysis on top: which machines are most likely to fail soon, and roughly how much run-time they have left. Keeping each asset's operating hours current feeds both the usage-based service intervals and those forecasts. The rule-based schedules you set on an asset (\"grease every 250 hours\") are the hands-on counterpart to the automatic forecasts — use both.\n\n## Sending Tooling Out for Outside Work\n\nWhen a mold or fixture has to leave the shop for outside work — a mold goes out to be re-cut, a fixture out for plating or heat-treat, then comes back — you're sending out one step, not handing off the whole part. That send-out and receive-back is tracked on the job and its operations, not on the asset record itself.\n\nWhat this means for you at the asset level: while the tooling is out, set its status to Maintenance or Out of Service so nobody schedules a run on a mold that isn't in the building, and log a downtime event if you're totaling the hours it was unavailable. When it comes back and is proven good, set it back to Active. The outside-work paperwork (who has it, what step, when it's due back) is handled where the job lives; the asset screen is just where you flag that the tool is off the floor.\n\n## Turning Assets and Its Extras On or Off\n\nThe asset register, preventive maintenance, and downtime tracking are separate pieces you can run independently. A shop can track equipment without the downtime log, or run schedules without downtime, and so on — how much you use is a setup choice. If part of this doesn't appear for you, or you don't see the management actions (creating schedules, logging maintenance), it's usually because that piece isn't turned on for your shop or your sign-in doesn't include it. Ask whoever set up your install; there's nothing broken on your end.\n\n## Photos and Sharing an Asset\n\n- **Photo** — attach a cover photo so the record is easy to recognize at a glance. A clear shot of the machine, the mold, or its nameplate is worth more than the name alone when two units look alike.\n- **Sharing** — you can send a coworker a link that opens straight to one asset, so they land on the right record instead of searching for it. Handy when you're telling a tech \"go look at this machine\" — send the link and they're one click from its history, status, and maintenance record. The other list screens work the same way.","sections":[]}"""
